INSERT INTO `artist_master` VALUES (1,'Test Artist','artist_1606902727.jpeg','',1,'','','y','a','2020-12-02 15:22:07','2020-12-02 15:23:16'),(2,'Mahbubur Rahman','artist_1606906951.jpeg','',4,'','','n','a','2020-12-02 16:32:31','2020-12-02 19:37:00'),(3,'Youdhisthir Maharjan','artist_1606907167.jpeg','Youdhisthir Maharjan reclaimed  book pages',8,'&lt;p style=&quot;text-align:justify&quot;&gt;Youdhistir Maharjan works with reclaimed book pages and text, making evocative collages that speak to those who look closely. His artistic practice exemplifies contemplation, commitment, and timelessness. His inspiration starts with the book itself, both with its potential meaning as well as its physicality. He goes to second-hand bookstores and browses until a book title attracts him. He buys it, takes home and begins working with it. Coming into visual art from creative writing, his approach to art is multilayered. Youdhi mentions Samuel Becket&amp;rsquo;s Waiting for Godot having a powerful impact on him at the start of his artistic endeavor. It is not the story that his art conveys but an impression, or idea and a process, which he shares with audience so they can discover their own interpretations for themselves. The process of making these collages is truly astounding and takes the artist&amp;rsquo;s full attention, unwavering focus, and repetitive physical labor to complete each piece over long time. He uses tedious actions like cutting out individual letters, piercing single book pages, pasting letters, weaving, and concealing some of the text over, and over. Remarkably, this monotonous toiling brings him joy and fulfillment. The process reveals the artist&amp;rsquo;s skill and aesthetic vision in the intricate works he creates.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align:justify&quot;&gt;Youdhisthir Maharjan currently resides between Boston and Kathmandu. He holds a BA in creative writing from New England College and an MFA in art history from the University of Idaho. His work has been shown in Nepal, India, and the United States, most recently as a solo exhibition at Vadehra Art Gallery in New Delhi in collaboration with Blueprint12, participated in the Serendipity Art Festival in Goa and in The Power of Intention: Reinventing the (Prayer) Wheel exhibition at the Rubin Museum of Art, New York.&lt;/p&gt;','','n','a','2020-12-02 16:36:07','2020-12-06 20:11:57'),(4,'Arshi Irshad Ahmadzai','artist_1606974582.jpeg','Arshi Irshad Ahmadzai artist contemporary',1,'&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Arshi Irshad Ahmadzai&amp;rsquo;s works are deeply connected to the experiences of women that rarely find a voice and are subdued under societal and political pressures or are bound within religious orthodoxies. Her works, though narrate a personal experience, are inspired by a much larger community of women who have been marginalized in history. Working within a disciplined studio practice and through collaborative community projects such as Lihaaf (Quilt), Arshi has struck a powerful chord with contemporary feminist art theory.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Her prolific art practice finds its foundation on the muslin cloth, a medium that is used to learn the art of stitching by the rafoogars (quilters) of Najibabad. Surrounded by a large community of women who share their embroidery over songs, compassion and sisterhood, it was only natural for Arshi to turn to the cloth rather than canvas. These exchanges have led to large scrolls as well as smaller works, where she juxtaposes image and text to comment on women and their roles, their sexuality, their freedom and their desires- some in love and some victims to political terrorism. An avid reader of poetry and philosophy, she not only questions patriarchy, but demands that her voice is heard and accepted.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Arshi Irshad Ahmadzai graduated with a Bachelors in Fine Art from the Aligarh Muslim University, 2011 and a Masters in Fine Art from Jamia Millia Islamia, New Delhi in 2013. Her recent exhibitions include &amp;lsquo;Seeds are being sown&amp;rsquo; at Shrine Empire Gallery, 2020; The India Art Fair, 2020; &amp;lsquo;Out of your shadow&amp;rsquo; by Blueprint12 at Gallery Espace, 2019 and a solo presentation at 1Shanthi Road Gallery in 2019. She is one of the recipients of the Five Million Incidents grant from the Goethe-Institut, New Delhi and the Inlaks Fine Arts Award in 2019.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;She lives between Kabul and New Delhi.&lt;/p&gt;','','n','a','2020-12-03 11:19:42','2020-12-04 16:45:18'),(5,'Kinglsey Gunatillake','artist_1607097084.jpeg','Book art titled Democracy by Sri Lankan contemporary artist',2,'&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;As one of the leading abstractionists of his country, Kingsley Guantilake&amp;rsquo;s has a dual practice - of his canvases and paperworks exploring forms and colour theories, and artist&amp;nbsp;books, which focus on the long and terrorised history of Sri Lankan civil war, leaving a trail of dead memories and empty bullets amidst promises of reconciliation by politicians in its wake. Gunatilake questions the aftermath of war, consequences of destruction and explosion, and the rationality left in their inheritance.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;Be it his abstract paintings or his &amp;lsquo;wounded&amp;rsquo; books, Kingsley&amp;rsquo;s works are sensory responses to the experience of violence, as well as the perpetration of acts of violence. His prolific methodology is quick and aggressive and consistently resisting statist, dominant narratives that exist in a post-war era. The spine of his book practice is inspired from the burning of the Jaffna Library in 1981, which is reiterated through a meditative practice of burning and cutting; an act of remembering and that of a witness.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;Born in Wadduwa, Sri Lanka, Kingsley now works in his studio out of Kandy in his native country and in Colombo. Gunatilake received a Bachelor in Fine Art from Fine Art University, Colombo and a Diploma in Environmental Education from the University of Strathclyde, Glasgow in 1994. His recent solo exhibitions include &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;lsquo;Yen&amp;rsquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt; at the Saskia Fernando Gallery, Colombo (2020); &amp;lsquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Wounded Book&amp;rsquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt; at Vadehra Art Gallery, New Delhi (2019); &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;lsquo;In Between&amp;rsquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt; at the Saskia Fernando Gallery, Colombo (2019) and &amp;lsquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Finding Space&amp;rsquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt; at at the Saskia Fernando Gallery, Colombo (2017). His group presentations include &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;India Art Fair&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt; (2017-2020); 4th Jeju Art Exhibition, Korea (2020); &amp;lsquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Days we Screamed&amp;rsquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt; at Red Dot Art Gallery, Colombo (2019); &amp;lsquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;K K Exhibition&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&amp;rsquo; at Fugentei Gallery, Kumamoto (2017); &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;lsquo;Reading Room&amp;rsquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt; at The Winchester Gallery, Winchester (2016); and &lt;em&gt;&amp;lsquo;Making History-Colombo Art Biennale&amp;rsquo;&lt;/em&gt;, Colombo (2014). He is the recipient of two NOMA Awards in Japan and the award for illustration from Biennale Bratislava, Slovakia. He has also received the Bunka award for his exceptional conservation work at the Temple of the Tooth, Kandy. Kingsley lives and works between Colombo and Kandy, Sri Lanka.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;','&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;Recent Solo exhibitions:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Libre Baskerville&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:#000000&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;lsquo;Yen